<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910122-0081</DOCNO><DOCID>910122-0081.</DOCID><HL>   Fannie Mae Will Provide   Financing to Home Builders</HL><DATE>01/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><CO>   FNM</CO><IN>DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)</IN><GV>U.S. GOVERNMENT AGENCY FINANCINGS -- NON-TREASURY (AGN)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Federal National Mortgage Associationwill begin providing its first construction financing forsingle family homes to help ease the credit crunch for homebuilders.   Under a $100 million pilot program unveiled yesterday,Fannie Mae will fund as much as 50% of residentialconstruction loans originated by commercial banks andthrifts. Fannie Mae has allocated $50 million for theprogram.</LP><TEXT>   To limit exposure, Fannie Mae will be the first lender tobe repaid when the homes are sold.   Fannie Mae, a government-chartered company that buysmortgages and packages them for resale as securities, hasnever before made direct construction loans. The program wasdeveloped at the suggestion of the National Association ofHome Builders.   &quot;The mortgage market is healthy,&quot; said NAHB spokesman JayShackford. &quot;It's the working capital that builders need upfront for buying land and building that has really dried up.&quot;   The new funding will provide only a tiny percentage of thecosts in the more than $100 billion-a-year home buildingmarket.</TEXT></DOC>